New Rules for the World Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let's imagine the leading world politicians would once again gather in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
They would naturally focus first on today's problems: the crisis in the Eurozone, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, dealing with these issues would force the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the overall solidity of the world economic arrangements.
Here are seven common-sense principles for global economic management that they might possibly agree upon.
(I discuss these in greater detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. The markets must be deeply embedded in existing control systems.
The idea that markets regulate themselves has suffered a fatal blow from the recent financial crisis and should be permanently buried.
Markets need other social institutions that support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies that establish and enforce rules.
They depend on the stabilizing functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They need the political acceptance generated by progressive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all of this applies equally to global markets.
2. In the foreseeable future, a democratic state leadership will likely remain largely organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives on, even if it may weaken somewhat, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile endeavor.
Dass die nationalen Regierungen erhebliche Kontrollgewalt an die transnationalen Institutionen abgeben, ist kaum zu erwarten; zudem würde eine Regelharmonisierung Gesellschaften mit unterschiedlichen Bedürfnissen und Präferenzen nichts nutzen.
Die Europäische Union könnte die einzige Ausnahme von diesem Axiom sein, obwohl ihre gegenwärtige Krise es eher zu belegen scheint.
Allzu oft verschwenden wir internationale Zusammenarbeit auf übertrieben ehrgeizige Ziele. Dabei kommen letztlich schwache Ergebnisse heraus, die den kleinsten gemeinsamen Nenner zwischen den großen Ländern darstellen.
Wenn internationale Zusammenarbeit „erfolgreich“ ist, bringt sie Regeln hervor, die entweder zahnlos sind oder die Präferenzen der mächtigeren Länder widerspiegeln.
Die Baseler Regeln über die Kapitalanforderungen und die Regeln der Welthandelsorganisation zu Subventionen, geistigem Eigentum und Investitionsmaßnahmen typisieren diese Art von übertriebenem Ehrgeiz.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic procedures within our own countries, rather than destroying them.

3. Pluralistic prosperity: The acknowledgment that the central institutional infrastructure of the global economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best suit their needs.
The United States, Europe, and Japan have long-term comparable prosperity.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social protection, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – one every decade – is then presented as the great success to which one should aspire.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experimentation and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A global economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will tend to foster rather than suppress such experimental openness and evolutionary development.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may seem innocuous.
But they carry powerful implications that clash with the prevailing views of globalization advocates.
Such an implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries were not provided with the tools to shape and preserve their own institutions – in other words, to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries can retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect the health and safety of consumers – and that they should be allowed to do so by possibly erecting barriers at their borders when trade is demonstrably threatening domestic practices that enjoy broad public support.
If globalization advocates are correct, the call for such protective measures will fail due to lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve to ensure that conflicting values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of retaining national regulations – both receive appropriate attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or the financial sector to preserve values and rules in their own country should not be confused with the use of such restrictions to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
Similarly, they should not enable the United States or the EU to use trade sanctions or other pressure tools to change labor market rules, environmental policies, or financial regulations in other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.

6. International agreements on economic cooperation to regulate the interaction between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the fundamental regulatory functions of the global economy does not mean that we should do without international rules.
The Bretton Woods system had clear rules, although they were limited in scope and depth.
A completely catch-as-catch-can approach would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the global economy, which help vehicles of different size, shape, and speed to overtake each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive to achieve a maximum of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot count on the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this actually takes place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
For undemocratic states, other, less liberal rules must therefore apply.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most importantly, they must accept the ultimate paradox that each of these principles illustrates: globalization works best when it is not taken too far.
